{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507877"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:58:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:58:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2682"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2682"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.06,0.39,0.26,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2682"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54065"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2682"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2682"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39538"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"182"},{"type":"tags","id":"1553"},{"type":"tags","id":"1554"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16305"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54065"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of increasing shortness of breath and swelling of his legs. He has a medical history of chronic kidney disease, atrial fibrillation, mechanical mitral valve replacement, and congestive heart failure. His regular medications include warfarin, furosemide, and metoprolol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly dyspnoeic. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His heart sounds are dual with no added murmurs. He has bibasal crackles present in the lung bases. There is 2+ pitting oedema present up to the mid-shin bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EComplete blood count and electrolytes are within normal limits. His international normalised ratio (INR) is 11.0 (0.9-1.2). On review, there is no evidence of bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management of his supratherapeutic INR?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Omit the next dose of warfarin and monitor INR daily","Lower the dose of warfarin by 25% and monitor INR daily","Hold the warfarin and administer 3 mg of vitamin K orally","Hold the warfarin and administer 3 mg of vitamin K and prothrombin complex concentrate","Hold the warfarin and administer 3 mg of vitamin K, prothrombin complex concentrate, and fresh frozen plasma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an exacerbation of congestive heart failure and a significantly supratherapeutic INR of 11.0. The most appropriate management in this case is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ehold the warfarin and administer 3 mg of vitamin K orally\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach aligns with current guidelines for managing supratherapeutic INR \u0026gt;10 with no evidence of bleeding and a low risk of bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOmitting the next dose of warfarin and monitoring INR daily\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient for an INR this high. This approach might be appropriate for mildly elevated INRs (\u0026lt; 4.5) without significant bleeding but not for an INR of 11.0.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELowering the dose of warfarin by 25% and monitoring INR daily\u003C/strong\u003E is also inadequate for this level of INR elevation. Like the previous option, this might be suitable for less severe elevations in INR, but not for an INR of 11.0.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHolding the warfarin and administering 3 mg of vitamin K and prothrombin complex concentrate \u003C/strong\u003Eis more aggressive than necessary in this case. Prothrombin complex concentrate is typically reserved for :\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epatients with INR \u0026gt;10 and a high risk of bleeding\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EINR \u22652 with clinically significant but non-life-threatening bleeding\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EINR \u22651.5 with life-threatening bleeding\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENone of these scenarios apply to the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHolding the warfarin and administering 3 mg of vitamin K, prothrombin complex concentrate, and fresh frozen plasma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most aggressive approach and is not warranted in this situation. This combination is typically used only for patients with life-threatening bleeding, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle in managing supratherapeutic INR is to balance the risk of bleeding against the risk of thrombosis. In this case, with no active bleeding and no high-risk features, administering vitamin K alone is sufficient to gradually bring down the INR while minimizing the risk of overcorrection and subsequent thrombosis. Vitamin K works by restoring the body\u0027s ability to produce its own clotting factors, which provides a more controlled reversal of anticoagulation compared to factor replacement therapies like prothrombin complex concentrate or fresh frozen plasma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with an INR\u003E10 and no bleeding with a low risk of bleeding, warfarin should be ceased and 3-5mg of vitamin K should be administered orally or intravenously.","Vitamin K administration is the primary treatment for supratherapeutic INR without significant bleeding, as it restores the body\u0027s ability to produce clotting factors."],"references":["Tran HA, Chunilal SD, Harper PL, Tran H, Wood EM, Gallus AS; Australasian Society of Thrombosis and Haemostasis (ASTH). An update of consensus guidelines for warfarin reversal. Med J Aust. 2013 Mar 4;198(4):198-9. doi: 10.5694/mja12.10614. PMID: 23451962."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39538"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2682"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39538"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-29T13:10:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-29T13:12:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2682"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54065"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suit